  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How much does it cost to register a trademark in the U.S.?",
  "response": "Registering a trademark in the United States involves several costs, primarily associated with filing fees charged by the United States Patent and Trademark Office (USPTO). Here's a breakdown of the typical expenses you can expect:\n\n### **1. USPTO Filing Fees**\n\nThe USPTO offers different application forms, each with its associated fees. The two most common are:\n\n- **TEAS Plus Application**\n  - **Cost:** **$250 per class of goods or services**\n  - **Features:**\n    - Requires adherence to strict filing requirements.\n    - Must select your goods or services from the USPTO's [Acceptable Identification of Goods and Services Manual](https://www.uspto.gov/trademarks-application-process/acceptable-identification-goods-and-services).\n    - Limited opportunities to amend application details after submission.\n  - **Best For:** Applicants who have clearly defined goods or services that match the USPTO's predefined categories and prefer a lower filing fee.\n\n- **TEAS Standard Application**\n  - **Cost:** **$350 per class of goods or services**\n  - **Features:**\n    - Provides more flexibility in describing goods or services.\n    - Allows for some amendments after submission.\n  - **Best For:** Applicants who need to provide custom descriptions for their goods or services or anticipate the need for adjustments during the application process.\n\n**Note:** A \"class\" refers to a category of goods or services. If your trademark covers multiple classes, you'll need to pay the filing fee for each one. For example, a trademark covering both apparel (Class 25) and footwear (Class 25) would require one class\u2014each distinct category counts separately.\n\n### **2. Additional Costs**\n\nWhile the USPTO filing fees are the primary costs, there may be additional expenses to consider:\n\n- **Attorney Fees:** Although not mandatory, many applicants hire trademark attorneys to navigate the complexities of the registration process. Attorney fees can range from **$500 to $2,000 or more**, depending on the attorney\u2019s experience and the complexity of your application.\n\n- **Responding to Office Actions:** If the USPTO identifies issues with your application, you'll receive an Office Action requiring a response. Addressing these may incur additional costs, especially if legal assistance is needed.\n\n- **Maintenance Fees:** Once your trademark is registered, there are periodic maintenance fees to keep the registration active:\n  - Between the **5th and 6th year**: $425 per class.\n  - Between the **9th and 10th year**, and every **10 years** thereafter: $425 per class.\n\n### **3. Estimated Total Costs**\n\n- **DIY Filing (Single Class):**\n  - **TEAS Plus:** $250\n  - **TEAS Standard:** $350\n\n- **With Attorney Assistance (Single Class):**\n  - **Total Estimated Cost:** Approximately **$750 to $2,350**, depending on the attorney's fees and any additional services required.\n\n### **4. Tips to Manage Costs**\n\n- **Research Thoroughly:** Ensure your trademark is unique to avoid disputes, which can lead to costly legal challenges.\n  \n- **Choose the Right Application Type:** If possible, use the TEAS Plus application to benefit from lower fees.\n\n- **Consider Professional Help Carefully:** While hiring an attorney adds to the upfront cost, it can save time and prevent errors that might lead to complications or additional expenses down the line.\n\n### **Conclusion**\n\nRegistering a trademark in the U.S. can cost anywhere from **$250 to $350 per class** in USPTO filing fees, plus any additional costs for legal assistance and maintenance. Carefully planning and understanding the process can help manage and potentially reduce the overall expenses involved in securing your trademark.\n\nIf you need detailed, personalized advice, it's recommended to consult with a qualified trademark attorney or the USPTO directly.",
